{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"577"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/577"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.31,0.51,0.01,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17317"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-week history of lower back pain that has become increasingly severe over the last 24 hours. He has been unable to pass urine or open his bowels for 24 hours. He also reports a six-month history of haemoptysis, weight loss, and anorexia. His medical history includes melanoma (excised), hypertension, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. His regular medications are amlodipine and tamsulosin. He is an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination of the lower limbs demonstrates reduced power and reflexes throughout.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol 1 g every 4 hours","Dexamethasone 8 mg intravenously","MRI spine","Intramuscular vitamin B12 injection","Urgent neurosurgical referral"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of cauda equina syndrome, which is a medical emergency requiring urgent diagnosis and management. The most appropriate initial step, as per current guidelines, is to perform an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine\u003C/strong\u003E. This will confirm the diagnosis, identify the level and extent of compression, and guide further management. Note that, if an MRI is not available, then a CT scan should be conducted. However, in this question there is no indication that MRI is not available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of the management of suspected spinal cord compression, particularly if there is a delay in obtaining an MRI or if metastatic disease is strongly suspected. However, it should not delay imaging. High-dose corticosteroids can be initiated once the diagnosis is confirmed by MRI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent neurosurgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E will likely be necessary, but only after the MRI has confirmed the diagnosis and provided details about the nature and extent of the compression. The neurosurgical team will need this information to plan any potential surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate for pain management in this scenario and does not address the underlying pathology. While pain management is important, it should not delay definitive diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular vitamin B12 injection\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord due to B12 deficiency. However, this typically presents with a more gradual onset of symptoms and would not explain this patient\u0027s acute urinary and bowel retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history of melanoma and recent symptoms of haemoptysis, weight loss, and anorexia raise concern for potential metastatic disease, possibly from a primary lung cancer given his significant smoking history. This further emphasises the need for urgent imaging to guide management. After the MRI, depending on the findings, the patient may require a multidisciplinary approach involving neurosurgery, radiation oncology, and medical oncology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urgent MRI spine is indicated in suspected cauda equina syndrome.","Cauda equina syndrome is a medical emergency requiring prompt diagnosis and management.","Metastatic spinal cord compression should be considered in patients with a history of cancer presenting with new neurological symptoms."],"references":["Kuris EO, McDonald CL, Palumbo MA, Daniels AH. Evaluation and Management of Cauda Equina Syndrome. Am J Med. 2021 Aug 30:S0002-9343(21)00506-4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34473966/","Germon T, Ahuja S, Casey ATH, Todd NV, Rai A. British Association of Spine Surgeons standards of care for cauda equina syndrome. Spine J. 2015 Mar 2;15(3 Suppl):S2-S4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25708139/","Emergency Care Institute - Agency for Clinical Innovation. Acute Low Back Pain. NSW Health. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/orthopaedic-and-musculoskeletal/acute-low-back-pain"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T16:58:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T20:37:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56129"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":